title: For Sale:  Walther P38 9MM (3rd Zero Series)
postcontent:
This is an excellent example of the very desirable fourth developmental stage, "Zero" Series P-38 pistol (usually called 3rd Model Zero-Series). All of these Zero series P-38 pistols are very significant as they track the various production changes that occurred throughout the early production cycle at the Walther factory. These fourth stage pistols went through numerous design changes on the frame, slide and locking block area to improve the produce ability and lower the overall production cost of these pistols. This fourth stage became the final production model that became the standard P-38 production pistol which was used though out WWII. These Zero series pistols are characterized by the "0" in front of the serial numbers, the high-polish commercial blue finish, with commercial type slide markings on the left side with the German Walther factory Waffenamt proofs on the right side. The grips are made of a black plastic/bakelite material with checkered panels on both sides with a rounded lanyard ring on the lower left side. The left side of the slide is marked with the Walther Banner followed by "P.38" and the serial number, "011073",  with a single Nazi Eagle firing proof. The various parts all carry a small Eagle Walther proof with a matching serial number on the front of the barrel lug, left side of the frame and left side of the slide. It is fitted with a correct matching locking block that carries the last three digits "073" of the serial number, along with a single Eagle Waffenamt on the right side. It is complete with one wartime magazine with the Walther proof and "P38 9MM" located on the lower left side of the magazine body, with an original 1941 dated P-38 holster. Not only was this manufactured by hand, but this was one of the 9500 made in this series and was made between Jan. 1940 & April 1940. Many considered the "Zero Series" to be the First Military P38's. After the war, it was later imported to the United States by PW ARMS of REDMON, WA and possibly used by one of our many Police Forces. The price I am listing is the mid price auction value/OBO. The reason for this is due to the fact that I will NOT ship this to any one under any circumstances. I understand there is insurance, but that will not replace this piece of history. 

Thank you for taking the time and consideration to look at my add.

title: For Sale:  M1 Carbine, USGI - Inland with extras
postcontent:
Selling a M1 Carbine. If you have never shot one, you are missing a great experience and piece of our military history. This carbine is an Inland. It is an original USGI with no import marks and came from CMP a few years back. It has a low 900K serial number so was made in early WWII. Stock is walnut and in good shape but shows it has been around.

I am selling it with 50-rds ammo, one 30-round magazines, and a carbine pouch with two-15 round magazines (15-round mags are loaded with ammo). It also includes the sling and oiler.

Will also make available to buyer additional 15- and 30-round magazines and several boxes of carbine ammo at very reasonable prices if desired.

I had no intent of selling any of my carbines but with the craziness in Colorado (proposed high-capacity mag ban, limitations on private sales, etc.), I figured here is a chance for someone to get a great piece of history and with 15- and 30-round magazines legally at a fair price.

If you are not familiar with the M1 Carbine, you should check them out. These are America’s first real a$$ault rifle. My favorite gun to shoot - they always go to the shooting range.

Please send me a message if you have questions. Not interested in trades and price is firm. 

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  M1 Carbine USGI - Inland - Sale pending
postcontent:
Selling a M1 Carbine. If you have never shot one, you are missing a great experience and piece of our military history. This carbine is an Inland. It is an original USGI with no import marks and came from CMP a few years back. It has a low 900K serial number so was made in early WWII. Stock is walnut and in good shape but shows it has been around.

I am selling it with 50-rds ammo, one 30-round magazines, and a carbine pouch with two-15 round magazines (15-round mags are loaded with ammo). It also includes the sling and oiler.

Will also make available to buyer additional 15- and 30-round magazines and several boxes of carbine ammo at very reasonable prices if desired.

I had no intent of selling any of my carbines but with the craziness in Colorado (proposed high-capacity mag ban, limitations on private sales, etc.), I figured here is a chance for someone to get a great piece of history and with 15- and 30-round magazines legally at a fair price.

If you are not familiar with the M1 Carbine, you should check them out. These are America’s first real a$$ault rifle. My favorite gun to shoot - they always go to the shooting range.

Please send me a message if you have questions. Not interested in trades and price is firm. 

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  9mm, 40 S&W, 45 Auto.  American Bullet AMMO
postcontent:
Well, you guys spoke your minds.....  I knew we would not prevail.....  GUys, Kim B is just the sales rep who sold it to me...  the owners DICK and Mary are the ones who need to hear your words....


The final straw:  Dick  Wrote:

Mr. Rojohn
I was traveling last week and was not able to respond to your email.  I was working with Kim to try to find a way to fill your order and satisfy your requests as best we could.  Our costs of materials have been rising every month and like all other ammunition manufacturers, we must raise our prices as our costs increase.

Having said that, with the number of threats we have received from your customers and the foul language that has been spewed to our staff, I have determined that we will not fill the order and will not be taking future orders from your firm.  I will not subject our staff to such verbal abuse.  They work hard to build high quality ammunition and serve our customers and do not deserve this kind of treatment.

We appreciate your past business and wish you the best in finding a supplier that can better suit your needs.

Richard  

I wrote:

Dick,

Thank you for your late response. Would have been great to hear from you sooner... I can not control what my customers do.  They are the buyers, and they have every reason to be pissed off as hell.  As for the cost of your product.  When a offer is made and a price is negotiated between two groups and the seller out of the blue changes the price by 18-20% that is called poor business.  It is funny but I can still pick up a box of .22lr from my dealer here in town... at  wholesale prices...  Funny how the price did not go up 18% after I made the purchase. I walk into bass pro shop once a week.  Price Tag does not say 25.00 dollars for a box of target ammo..  it still has the same price tag....  

 Your folks do build a quality product,  I will give you that, but what you need to work on is the second part of your email below.  Serve your customers.  You sir are doing a horrible job at that.  Your customers do not deserve to be screwed the way you are screwing them...  But hey, you run it the way you see fit.... see how long you stay up and running....  The  BBB will be called, emailed, so on so forth....You broke a verbal contract that we had 12 weeks ago for 70 cases of ammo.  We were told that it would be done in 6-8 weeks.  YOU BROKE A CONTRACT we had...  and folks will hear about it....

Dick you mention that you will not take future orders from my company.  LOL!  Do you really think that a person will really come back just to get screwed again?  After this, I would never come back....I could by buy Tula ammo and be treated better than your company has treated these 70+ buyers....

I will pass along your email to the 70 folks, down here in Kansas/ Missouri and let them do what angry folks do when they are  wronged....  I am sorry that Kim had to take a few bad phone calls, I guess those Nebraska buyers can get a bit angry as well when it comes to getting hosed on a contract.... 

Mary   Wrote:

Mr. Rojohn,

I may be a little behind the curve here as I know there has been communication going on since you sent this email to me last Friday but this is the first opportunity that I have had to respond to  you so please forgive me for the delay.  I am not sure what price you were quoted and I am sorry that you are feeling that our price increase is out of line.  Our goal is to continue to make high quality ammunition.  Unfortunately, the components that we need to produce our ammunition is the best American made that we can find and probably because of the recent ammunition shortage,  the prices of these high quality components have increased dramatically.  We have made a decision not to compromise and not to settle for something less than the best.  Consequently, our production prices have increased dramatically.  All of our customers have been very  understanding and supportive of this decision as they love our product.  We have been told by many shooters that our ammunition is the cleanest, most reliable on the market.  We are very proud of American Bullet  and we will continue to uphold our high standards in production so that we can continue producing our high quality product.  I am very sorry that we cannot fill your order at your anticipated price.  At one point earlier today, we were anxious to contact you and offer you something that we think you have found to be very agreeable.  However, because of the way  that our employees have been treated by people that know you, I think it would be difficult for us to continue any type of a respectful, trusting relationship. 

Sincerely,
Mary Abramson

I replied with:

Thanks but we will take our 70 cases to another vendor. I buy ammo from numerous locations. No price increase except you. I will agree that you make a quality ammo but your outrageous increase after a price was agreed upon twelve weeks ago is a breach of a contract. So the loss of a respectful trusting relationship is on American Bullet not me. You rattled 70 cages by your poor decision. This is on you. You broke a contract.... I will be posting all of this information in the add I wrote up to sell your product. All I can do as a dealer is provide the best information to my customers and at this point I can not do that. I apologized to Kim for my customers.... Maybe you should apologize to my customers who had faith in American Bullet just to be let down. The price quote I was given were the 2012 price sheet. 18-20% less than what they are now. I will stick beside my customers and fight for them just like you fight for your sales reps. In the end the customers are the ones buying your products not your employee's. I have started a complaint with the BBB and the folks who made these purchases will join in to make sure others to not fall in your price gouging.
MR.

So let the refunds begin...  I want to apologize to everyone once again... I provided you all with the hopes of getting ammo through a company that made a quality product... however, they do not stand behind an contract between the sales department and myself.  I will be cutting all affiliation with American Bullet.  I have 70 some customers who have been wronged...  I will start the refund process today once I contact my banks....  I will be working in the same order that purchases were made.  Please be patient......I will get your money back to you....


Matt

The M6A2™ rifle’s edge in capability, reliability, accuracy and long service life is the result of advanced technology materials and manufacturing processes, combined with progressive patented designs. title: For Sale:  M48 8mm Mauser matching serial numbers - excellent condition
postcontent:
M48 8mm Mauser. All the serial numbers match and the condition is remarkable considering the age of this rifle.  The bore is shiny and bright, no signs of pitting.  I think you would be hard pressed to find another M48 that looks this good and hasn't been refinished.  

Also included is a half box of Rem 170gr soft pt core-lokt ammo.  

More info about these guns from the web.


These Rifles were produced by Yugoslavia at the Kragujevac arsenal, and were named the "Model 1948 98k Short Rifle" or the Yugoslavian M48. They were based in on the German 98k Mauser.
The M48 is a little shorter in overall length in the barrel and the overall length of the rifle than the German 98k

Manufactured by Yugoslavia into the 60's they became obsolete with the proliferation of the Automatic rifle. So they were lovingly stored for civil militia/reserve use, and test fired every 5 years. 50 years later they have been released on the collectors market.
Yugoslavia produced many of these rifles, and many are still available on the market in mint condition These 8mm rifles are extraordinary shooters that are well made and offer a unique opportunity to the shooter and collector to purchase a Like New version of the very dependable and well made Mauser 98k.
